description:
INGREDIENTS: 
1/4 cup ground oats
1/4 cup rolled oats
3 garlic cloves, peeled and minced
1 cup water
1/4 cup brown sugar
1 tablespoon tomato paste
Few pinches of smoked paprika
Few pinches of salt and pepper
1/2 cup crumbled firm tofu
Few drops of liquid smoke (optional)
Cooking oil
Side of rice and tomatoes (upon serving)

DIRECTIONS:
In a medium-sized pot, combine the ground oats, whole oats, garlic, water, tomato paste, brown sugar, and smoked paprika. You can also add a few drops of liquid smoke. Add a few punches of salt and pepper. 

Heat the pot over medium heat and constantly mix for about ten minutes or until the mixture is thick like a raw burger patty. Lower the heat and add the tofu crumbles and mix well. Adjust seasoning to taste. Turn off the heat and let the mixture cool down to the touch.

Using your hands, form into two-inch logs. 

Heat a medium size pan and fill with enough oil to cover the base of the pan. Once the oil is hot, fry the Longganisa logs. Be careful not to scorch them. They cook quickly, so keep tossing and turning using tongs or a ladle. Cook until theyre slightly brownish-red and slightly crunchy.

Turn off the heat and serve hot with rice and tomatoes garnish. 




Here is an updated version of my vegan longganisa recipe, this time using Quaker Oats as the binder!  I got the idea of using oats from a fellow vegan YouTuber, @EastMeetsKitchen who featured an oats sausages recipe from a wartime cookbook.
